<TEXT>
a 29year study of cancer in sweden 
shows the rate of cases increased faster among women than men 
especially skin cancer caused by too much sun 
malignant melanoma caused by overexposure to ultraviolet rays 
was increasing by 66 percent a year and ine 1987 represented 35 
percent of all cancer cases said jerzy einhorn of the karolinska 
hospital 
a law requiring doctors to report all cancer cases to a national 
registrar since 1958 has yielded a unique foundation for health 
care and planning since it covers 100 percent of the population in 
specific areas einhorn said 
the study released tuesday by the hospital covered stockholm 
and gotland a large rural island in the baltic 
sven tornqvist who was in charge of the register said the rate 
of all forms of cancer increased by 29 percent for women and 15 
percent for men in the swedish capital from 1958 to 1987 the 
figures were higher in gotland 
malignant melanoma could become the major form of cancer in 
the next century because many people who have damaged their skin 
have not yet developed the disease einhorn said 
he attributed the increase among swedes to their more frequent 
holiday trips to warmer countries and their penchant for sunbathing 
one reason for the general rising incidence of cancers is that 
people are living longer einhorn said 
lung cancer was the most common cancer but it decreased among 
men along with a decline in smoking 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

