<TEXT>
people at george bushs campaign 
rallies in southwestern michigan last year heard first from his 
foremost cheerleader peter secchia 
the outspoken and sometimes abrasive state republican party 
leader positioned himself at the podium for more than an hour 
before bushs arrival and led thousands of supporters in songs 
taunting democratic presidential nominee michael dukakis 
as michigans national committeeman since 1980 secchia never 
has been at a loss for words 
until now 
after months of tireless work on bushs behalf secchia was 
rewarded with a nomination as ambassador to italy 
it initially appeared the 52yearold italianamerican lumber 
magnate would sail through senate confirmation but secchias 
propensity for coarse humor and offcolor remarks have haunted him 
for example 
a few days after bushs selection of dan quayle to run as vice 
president secchia defended quayle amid rumors linking him 
romantically to a former female lobbyist if thats the only 
thing you can say about a 41yearold man that he danced close 
with a goodlooking woman then i think hell make one hell of a 
vice president 
secchia doesnt deny he made an offensive hand gesture to a 
political foe in the basement of a bar but after it was reported 
called it goodnatured political sparring 
a january 1988 harpers magazine article about the michigan 
gop portrayed secchia as a sexist and quoted him as making vulgar 
remarks about the size of a womans breasts secchia says he was 
misquoted 
in august 1988 secchia said of his political adversaries i 
know what sodomy is because thats what democrats are always doing 
to me 
secchia complains his comments have been misinterpreted and 
that some of the people now judging him in washington dont 
understand his humor 
theres been grumbling in italian newspapers over bushs 
selection of an ambassador who is an expert fundraiser with a 
sharp tongue but little foreign policy experience 
in the senate secchias confirmation vote was stalled until at 
