<TEXT>
a technique for infecting white rabbits with 
the aids virus has been developed by federal scientists providing 
researchers with a laboratory animal to test drugs and vaccines for 
combating the fatal disease 
dr thomas j kindt of the national institute of allergy and 
infectious diseases said tuesday that because of the new technique 
laboratories everywhere will be able to use the new zealand white 
rabbit as a model for studying infections of the human 
immunodeficiency virus which causes aids 
research into aids or acquired immune deficiency syndrome has 
been severely handicapped because there has been no animal model to 
test treatment agents for the disease 
kindt said the rabbit now can provide that model 
if you inject this animal with human cells infected with hiv 
the infection will take in the rabbit he said within four weeks 
after the injection the rabbits immune system starts showing 
signs of reacting to the virus a finding that is called 
seroconversion 
once this has occurred kindt said the rabbit could be used to 
test drug treatments for the disease 
kindt said the rabbit could also be used to test candidate aids 
vaccines 
we could inject the rabbit with the vaccine and then after a 
period of time challenge it with the hiv cells and see if it 
reacted to the virus he said 
until now the chimpanzee has been the only nonhuman animal 
that can contract true aids and thus could be used as a model for 
studying the disease but chimps are becoming increasing rare and 
now typically cost up to 60000 each said kindt new zealand 
white rabbits cost about 40 each and a good breeding pair can 
produce up to three litters a year generally with eight rabbits 
per litter 
a very immediate and urgent need exists for thousands of 
experimental animals to test promising agents already used 
effectively in test tubes and others proposed for use against 
aids said kindt 
the pharmaceutical manufacturers association has announced that 
there are at least 100 antiaids drugs vaccines and other agents 
that are stalled in development because there is no appropriate 
animal model available for testing 
kindt said that the rabbit when exposed to hiv develops some 
of the classic human symptoms of aids including enlarged lymph 
spleen and thymus glands and a decline in the numbers of healthy 
tcells one of the immune system cells 
typically he said a rabbit infected with aids can live for 
about a year unless it develops a major secondary infection which 
is common because aids destroys the immune system uninfected 
rabbits said kindt will live up to five years 
the method of giving the rabbit aids involves injecting it with 
about five million infected human cells seroconversion follows in 
about four weeks the process can be speeded up said kindt by the 
injection of about 50 million infected human cells 
kindt said that new studies need to be conducted to see if a 
rabbit infected with the aids virus can spread the disease to other 
rabbits through sexual intercourse a common way of spreading the 
disease among humans 
he said tests have shown that aids can be spread between the 
laboratory animals by injecting blood from an infected rabbit into 
another rabbit aids is often spread among human drug users who 
share needles or syringes 
kindt led a team of nih scientists that developed the technique 
to infect the laboratory rabbits others on the team are dr 
henrietta kulaga dr thomas m folks and rosamond a rutledge 
a license to commercially produce the laboratory rabbit for aids 
research has been given to rri inc a newly organized company by 
the nih kindt said the company plans to produce about 3000 
rabbits annually at a biologically secure laboratory in frederick 
md other facilities are to be built later in canada italy and 
japan to make the animal available to researchers worldwide 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

