<TEXT>
guitarist john cipollina a founder of 
the 60s rock band quicksilver messenger service has died of 
emphysema he was 45 
cipollina whose flowing melodic style represented the san 
francisco sound at its purest died monday at marin general 
hospital he had been taken there after he became short of breath 
at his home in mill valley 
born in berkeley cipollina lived in san salvador and guatemala 
as a child and moved to mill valley with his family at 6 
in 1965 he helped form quicksilver a group that was never as 
popular as san francisco bay area contemporaries the grateful dead 
and jefferson airplane but according to the encyclopedia of rock 
the band represented the epitome of the san francisco sound 
cipollina whose signature song was the bo diddley classic 
mona contributed some of the legendary instrumental jams of 
the era 
he left quicksilver in 1970 and later played with the band 
copperhead and the welsh band called man he also toured europe 
during the 1970s with fellow marin musician nick gravenites a 
former member of the san francisco band electric flag 
most recently cipollina had played with the dinosaurs a band 
consisting of former members of jefferson airplane country joe and 
the fish and big brother and the holding company 
his mother who survives him was a concert pianist and his 
godfather was pianist jose iturbi his younger brother mario is 
the bass player with huey lewis amp the news 
funeral plans are pending 
