this looks like any former company town in 
west virginia with parallel rows of virtually identical houses a 
small soapsudfilled creek flowing past back yards and a 
playedout mine 
but residents are worried about something unseen that sets 
minden apart it may be contaminated with cancercausing chemicals 
for years shafer equipment co removed oil from old electrical 
transformers they were rebuilding burning some oil for heat 
giving some to residents to use in furnaces and dumping the rest in 
a pit at the mouth of the former minden mine residents say 
the oil is laced with polychlorinated biphenyls known to cause 
cancer in laboratory animals pcbs bond to soil and are not 
watersoluble so any contaminated oil dumped 15 years ago could 
still present a health risk 
frequent floods along arbuckle creek which flows through town 
have dumped tons of mud from the plant into yards and basements 
oak hill a city of 9200 a few miles to the west also gets much 
of its water from the area 
when you sit and think that weve been exposed to this 
contamination for 15 years said resident sue workman im of 
the opinion there is no way they could ever clean it up 
the federal environmental protection agency has spent 3 million 
cleaning up the plant hauling away 4735 tons of contaminated 
dirt 110 drums of contaminated liquids and solids 23 drums of 
electric capacitors and 21 transformers said agency spokeswoman 
theresa bickel in philadelphia last month the agency agreed to 
test the soil within three miles of the site 
but some residents who have formed a group called concerned 
citizens to save fayette county think no amount of work will make 
the town safe they want a state or federal buyout of their town 
and creation of a new minden somewhere else at an estimated cost 
at 20 million 
money should that be a consideration when peoples lives are 
at stake asked workman 30 the mother of two 
simply moving is out of the question for most of the towns 300 
families because no one wants to buy a house here she said you 
cant give a piece of property away she said 
the epa soil study will begin in september and take at least six 
months said loretta haddy an epidemiologist with the state health 
department if high levels of pcbs are found the centers for 
disease control will investigate whether they have caused any 
health problems 
a state health department study of the towns mortality figures 
from 1979 to 1985 found nothing unusual 
but a study by vanderbilt university students last year came up 
with vastly different results 
the students found traces of pcbs in soil taken from 17 of 19 
sites they also surveyed 173 residents and found 62 percent of the 
women surveyed had suffered miscarriages or stillbirths or had 
children with birth defects 
