may 30 
the wichita kan eaglebeacon on gas guzzling cars 
sometime within the past decade americas idea of auto fuel 
conservation took a wide detour 
automobile dealerships in the late 1970s and early 1980s pushed 
small economysized vehicles that offered high gasoline mileage 
as gas prices decreased however americans traded their economy 
cars for new models that offered greater comfort and increased 
performance yet demanded more fuel 
already theres pressure aplenty to increase auto fuel 
efficiency 
these suggestions play into concerns of us foreign 
policymakers who fear the growing us dependence on cheap foreign 
oil leaves americans vulnerable to another energy crisis 
if the united states is to take a leadership role in efforts to 
slow the greenhouse effect strengthening us auto efficiency 
standards would demonstrate that commitment 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
may 30 
the albuquerque nm tribune on ending unfair trade 
no one who understands the benefits of an open world trading 
system can be pleased by president bushs designation last week of 
japan india and brazil as unfair trading nations but he had no 
good alternative to that risky action 
bush acted under a stiff provision of the 1988 trade law which 
requires him to name nations that maintain barriers to us 
exports if negotiations do not remove the barriers the president 
is authorized to retaliate 
if bush had not moved against japan which richly deserves to be 
called an unfair trader congress would have exploded with fury and 
might well have passed protectionist legislation that would have 
done even more harm 
japan which ran a 55 billion trade surplus with the united 
states last year was the main target but bush did not want to 
cite it alone fearing an irrational reaction by tokyo so brazil 
and india less flagrant offenders were added as cover 
japan has to change it cannot expect to sell cars and consumer 
electronics to americans and refuse to buy what they make best 
one hopes americans will have the patience and japanese will 
develop the maturity to prevent a titfortat trade war that will 
harm everybody 
</TEXT>
