<TEXT>
the world health organization marked its second 
notobacco day on wednesday and its leader said he was alarmed at 
the rising number of women smokers worldwide 
some countries also marked the day during which smokers were 
urged to give up cigarettes and chewing tobacco for 24 hours the 
theme of this years event was the female smoker at added risk 
antismokers in bangladesh announced the results of a smoking 
survey and soviet scientists appealed to women to quit smoking 
delegates to the congress of peoples deputies in moscow agreed to 
an appeal by one deputy to refrain from smoking inside the palace 
of congresses for the day 
dr hiroshi nakajima who directorgeneral said smoking posed 
greater health risks to women than to men and urged women not to 
seek a false expression of liberty through cigarettes 
women who take birthcontrol pills face increased risks of heart 
disease and strokes and pregnant women endanger the lives of their 
children he said at a news conference in geneva 
the death rate of women from lung cancer has risen by at least 
200 percent since the 1950s and more than 500000 women die each 
year as a result of smoking according to who figures 
the number of women who smoke increased markedly and became a 
concern after world war ii 
it is deplorable that while tobacco consumption by men is 
clearly decreasing in certain countries women are becoming the 
principle target of tobacco advertising nakajima said 
women are smoking more in a false expression of liberty 
equality and intellectual prestige unfortunately advertising is 
stimulating this tendency he said 
the un agency singled out for particular criticism cigarette 
brands aimed exclusively at women and promoted by images and words 
that imply glamour such as ultraslim or slender 
but nakajima ruled out an international agreement to regulate 
tobacco marketing similar to the one already adopted by the agency 
for baby formula 
he said such an agreement would be almost impossible because 
of opposition by many of whos 166 members including third world 
countries dependent on tobacco exports and industrialized countries 
that receive high tax revenues from tobacco 
nakajima said he was concerned about the trend in the third 
world where smoking is on the increase especially among educated 
women 
in a who survey of 40 countries the 10 with the highest female 
smoking rates were in the third world 
at the top of the list was papua new guinea where 80 percent of 
adult women smoke followed by swaziland in southern africa with 72 
percent according to the survey 
in bangladesh an antismoking group announced the results of a 
survey conducted in april that showed that about 5 million women in 
the country chew or smoke tobacco about 25 million people in the 
nation of 110 million smoke according to the group adhunik which 
means modern in the bengali language 
denmark where 39 percent of the women smoke topped the list of 
industrialized countries in whos survey followed by the 
netherlands with 33 percent the united states where 24 percent of 
the women smoke ranked 16th out of 25 industrialized countries 
who has called on doctors to help patients break the habit 
especially by setting an example themselves 
the agency estimates that 10 percent of us male doctors smoke 
an estimated 42 percent smoke in the soviet union 65 percent in 
the netherlands and 70 percent in poland 
the agency did not include female doctors in its figures 
who estimates that about 25 million people die each year as a 
result of smoking 
</TEXT>
