<TEXT>
stolen art works could pour into the united 
states if a us art dealer wins a lawsuit over four sixth century 
christian mosaics an attorney for the cypriot government said 
if all it takes to bring stolen art into this country is an 
empty head and a roundtrip ticket to switzerland the flood gates 
are open thomas r kline said tuesday the first day of a 
lawsuit in federal court pitting a suburban art dealer against 
cyprus and its greek orthodox church 
kline said art dealer peg goldberg had tried to claim that her 
inexperience in the international art trade legitimized her 
purchase of the stolen mosaics which once graced the walls of a 
church in the northern village of lythrankomi 
this is a case about a woman who fell in love with a work of 
art said joe c emerson goldbergs attorney he added that his 
client had sought to determine if the mosaics were stolen before 
purchasing them 
analysts have said the case could set a precedent governing 
international trade in national art treasures 
the mosaics are the work of an unknown artist and depict jesus 
as a boy the apostles matthew and james and an archangel 
goldberg paid 12 million for the mosaics in july 1988 to aydin 
dikmen a turk living in west germany 
emerson said the cypriot government knew in 1982 that dikmen had 
been linked to art thefts from northern cyprus which is under 
turkish control and could have pursued him earlier to recover the 
mosaics 
athanasis papageorghiou acting director of cypriot antiquities 
testified tuesday that he knew of dikmen through news reports but 
had no way of stopping him 
during testimony today papageorghiou reviewed a list of 28 
people his department had notified about the missing mosaics in 
1980 the 28 from around the world were specialists in 
byzantine art and in all probability they could be contacted if 
something was for sale he said 
asked about efforts the cypriot government had made to recover 
the mosaics papageorghiou said he was told government officials 
had not contacted interpol because they needed the name and 
location of the smuggler 
papageorghiou said the removal of the mosaics was part of a 
widespread pattern of looting in churches in northern cyprus which 
since 1975 has been controlled by the selfdesignated turkish 
republic of northern cyprus 
many churches are looted museums are looted private 
collections are looted we have suffered much papageorghiou said 
he testified that the government was informed the mosaics were 
missing in november 1979 and had notified the united nations 
museums and other organizations 
judge james e noland ruled that the turkish cypriots could not 
intervene in the case because their government was not recognized 
by the united states 
the case could rest on whether cyprus diligently sought the 
return of the mosaics and whether or not goldberg showed good 
faith in trying to determine if the works were stolen 
also important was whether the sale would be governed by swiss 
law or more stringent indiana laws regarding stolen property 
kline said evidence would show the sale was finalized in west 
germany he said indiana law should apply because four indiana 
residents stand to profit from the sale of the mosaics an indiana 
bank authorized the loan for the sale and the mosaics were in 
switzerland only a few days en route to their final destination 
goldberg has said she checked a stolen art registry in new york 
unesco officials in switzerland and customs officials in the united 
states turkey switzerland and turkish cyprus before buying the 
mosaics 
she does not recall the name of a single official to whom she 
spoke kline said she never called cyprus or the church of 
cyprus miss goldberg does appear to be in quite a hurry in this 
transaction 
