a new plan to integrate higher education 
in louisiana without closing or merging any colleges puts much of 
the burden of success or failure on a single governing board 
officials said wednesday 
replacing four boards with a single powerful one was pushed by 
gov buddy roemer over the objections of some black leaders who 
felt it would be insensitive to needs of students at the states 
two mostly black universities 
on tuesday a special master appointed by three federal judges 
to find a way to settle a 15yearold lawsuit against louisiana by 
the justice department submitted his final desegregation proposal 
for court approval 
paul verkuil president of william and mary college in virginia 
called for giving the governor power to appoint a 17member 
governing board subject to state senate confirmation verkuil said 
the board should include at least seven blacks show a geographic 
balance represent all schools and include a student 
unlike the states current board of regents the board would not 
share power with boards that oversee the mostly black southern 
university system the mostly white louisiana state university 
system and the smaller regional schools 
larry crain president of the board overseeing regional 
colleges said it will be up to the unified governing board to 
implement verkuils plan successfully 
it all depends on how the new board approaches this if they 
follow whats been laid out here it can happen the state is going 
to have to take this very seriously to bring about integration 
crain said 
sen william jefferson a new orleans lawyer who represents 
southern university at baton rouge one of the two mostly black 
universities said he had not received a copy of the plan 
i do know the single board has nothing to do with 
desegregation and it seems to be the centerpiece of this plan 
jefferson said 
thomas todd of chicago attorney for the other predominantly 
black college grambling state said he could not comment on the 
plan until he received a copy 
the plan would provide additional money to the mostly black 
universities to develop programs more attractive to white students 
it also would establish admission standards to funnel 
betterprepared students into selective universities and others 
into a new community college system currently any graduate of a 
louisiana high school can attend any state college 
jack andonie chairman of the lsu board of supervisors said 
these changes could advance desegregation somewhat but until 
they have some significant merging of some schools theres not 
going to be much integration 
