orders to factories for manufactured goods 
rose in april for the second straight month in the biggest increase 
since december the commerce department reported wednesday 
the strong 27 percent april gain followed a 07 percent hike in 
march and 12 percent and 2 percent declines in january and 
february orders had soared 47 percent in december 
total orders registered 2394 billion on a seasonably adjusted 
basis in april 
robert brusca an economist with nikko securities co 
international inc in new york compared the factory orders report 
with the index of leading economic indicators which commerce also 
released on wednesday 
factory orders were absolutely surprising he said while 
the indicators showed a slower 08 percent increase after falling 
for two months 
it means he said the porridge is not too hot not too 
cold and it isnt just right were just vacillating between the 
two i think 
bruce steinberg of merrill lynch capital markets in new york 
said the orders report means that in april the economy picked up 
from a depressed level in march 
and yet orders were not higher in april than in 
december steinberg said so although the industrial sector of 
the economy is still advancing it doesnt have anywhere the kind 
of momentum it had in 1988 
commerce said both durable and nondurable orders rose in april 
with durables up 3 percent to 1292 billion it said all major 
industries expect fabricated metals participated in the increase 
electrical machinery orders were up 93 percent to 20 billion 
primary metals such as steel up 6 percent to 126 billion and 
transportation equipment up 14 percent to 376 billion the 
highly volatile transportation segment was up 11 percent in march 
and down 76 percent in february 
orders for nondurable goods jumped 24 percent to 1102 
billion the department reported nearly half the increase was in 
the petroleum refining industry 
the overall increase would have been higher except for a 158 
percent drop in defense orders which are subject to wide swings 
depending on when big contracts are signed 
excluding defense orders rose 36 percent after falling 03 
percent in march and 27 percent in february 
