said in a statement 
since the first soviet ss20 missile destruction at kapustin 
yar in august us inspectors have witnessed the elimination of 
945 soviet missiles beginning with the sept 8 elimination at 
longhorn army ammunition plant near marshall texas soviet 
inspectors have been present for the destruction of 324 us inf 
missiles 
the treaty took effect on june 1 1988 and calls for the 
destruction of all intermediaterange nuclear missiles over a 
threeyear period those missiles have a range of roughly 300 miles 
to 3500 miles and the agreement to destroy them marked the first 
time the two superpowers had agreed to eliminate an entire class of 
nuclear weapons 
the agreement also marked the first time the united states and 
soviet union ever agreed to onsite or intrusive inspections 
to ensure compliance with an arms treaty 
when the treaty took effect the soviets had 1846 missiles in 
the intermediaterange category divided among six different types 
the united states had 846 missiles divided between pershing and 
groundlaunched cruise missiles 
according to the yearend statistics which were compiled by the 
defense departments onsite inspection agency both sides 
exercised their right to conduct 20 surprise inspections during the 
first year in addition to the normal inspections to witness 
destruction of missiles and to verify the final closure of inf 
missile facilities 
the soviets conducted 96 inspections during the year in western 
europe and the united states compared to 244 conducted by american 
inspectors at soviet sites 
both sides also succeeded during the first year in moving an 
inspection team from the other country into permanent housing 
facilities near missile plants the treaty specifies that up to 30 
inspectors may be located fulltime outside the gates of a missile 
production plant to guard against surreptious production of inf 
missiles 
in the case of the soviets they were provided housing 
facilities in west jordan utah on april 17 near a hercules plant 
at magna utah american inspectors moved into permanent housing in 
votkinsk near a missile plant on april 10 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890531-0153 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
greek and turkish cypriot leaders failed 
in nine months of talks to agree on reunifying the divided island 
before a thursday deadline and the united nations granted a 
threeweek extension 
officials said it was likely the un security council would be 
called in to mediate the deadlocked negotiations 
leaders of both communities are trying to establish a formula 
for a twostate federation under which the greek cypriot majority 
of 550000 people would share power with the 120000member turkish 
cypriot minority the greek side reportedly is pushing for a strong 
federal government while the turkish side wants a looser 
federation 
the two sides reportedly also disagree over the withdrawal of 
turkish troops and the right of 200000 greek cypriots to return 
to property they fled after the 1974 turkish invasion 
turkish cypriot leader rauf denktash president of the 
breakaway state in north cyprus that is recognized only by turkey 
said he would intensify efforts for international recognition if 
the talks break off 
the talks prevented our recognition by friends once they are 
broken off there will be no obstacles to our recognition 
denktash said 
greek cypriot leader george vassiliou president of the 
internationally recognized government of cyprus blamed turkish 
intransigence for the lack of progress 
we have submitted comprehensive proposals for the solution of 
all aspects of the cyprus problem vassiliou said tuesday 
world opinion agrees that our proposals are honorable reasonable 
and can lead to an agreement 
vassiliou said he favors mediation by the security council 
while denktash does not 
in 1974 a coup by greeces military junta failed on the island 
turkey invaded the northern part of cyprus saying it was 
protecting the minority turkish cypriot community and partitioned 
the east mediterranean island 
in the wake of the invasion 40000 turkish cypriots also moved 
north taking over the homes and properties of the greek cypriot 
refugees other property was given to an estimated 50000 settlers 
brought to cyprus from the turkish mainland 
denktash in 1975 proclaimed the northern part of the island an 
independent turkish state 
the two sides are divided by a heavily fortified green line 
manned by 13000 greek cypriot troops facing an estimated 30000 
turkish army soldiers and 10000 turkish cypriot soldiers 
the buffer zone extending 112 miles across the island is 
patrolled by a 2100member united nations peacekeeping force 
the two cypriot leaders agreed on the thursday deadline when 
they embarked on their negotiations during a meeting with perez de 
cuellar in geneva in august 
