<TEXT>
most israelis favor affirmative action for 
women tax breaks for child care and a longer school day to allow 
more mothers to work full time according to preliminary results of 
a survey conducted wednesday 
the informal survey described by israel radio as the most 
extensive done in israel was organized by naamat the womens 
organization of the histadrut trade union federation 
the goal was to demonstrate to prime minister yitzhak shamirs 
government and the public that there is strong support for naamats 
campaign for greater economic rights for women 
while the level of education of israeli women is comparable to 
that in other developed countries the womens movement has not won 
the same support here as in the united states and europe 
ethia simcha the prime ministers adviser on the status of 
women noted that 51 percent of all government workers are women 
but only 11 percent hold management jobs only 2 percent of all 
governmentrun companies are headed by women ms simcha said 
there is not enough consciousness about womens rights in this 
country said naamat spokeswoman carmel eytan one of the aims 
of the poll is to raise public debate on these questions 
ms eytan said more than 500000 surveys were turned in about 
onethird of them by men 
she said according to results based on about half the survey 
responses 
ninety percent support extending the school day past 2 pm so 
more mothers may work full time 
seventyfour percent approve of tax breaks for child care 
seventyfive percent support changes in the tax law that would 
allow women to file separate returns 
only about twothirds of the respondents support affirmative 
actions programs for women 
most people against were men she added 
israeli women and men lined up at about 2000 sites set up in 
banks day care centers supermarkets and on sidewalks across the 
country to take part in the survey 
at a busy intersection near a tel aviv shopping center 
organizers set up a cardboard box on the pavement in a 15minute 
period about 40 people dropped off questionnaires 
im really surprised by the number of people voting i dont 
know what ill do when our box is full said a naamat volunteer 
ms eytan said she hoped that several hundred thousand israelis 
over 18 would participate in the survey israel has a population of 
42 million 
</TEXT>
