<DOCNO> AP890531-0163 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
commercial banks must do more soon to help 
third world countries reduce their debts the head of the 
international monetary fund said wednesday in echoing comments of 
the bush administration 
imf managing director michel camdessus in some of his toughest 
comments on the subject told a gathering of bankers in paris that 
the time has come for the large internatinal banks to increase 
their contribution to the debt reduction program unveiled by 
treasury secretary nicholas brady on march 10 
it is urgent to set the strategy in motion without delay 
camdessus said in a speech to the french bankers association the 
text of his remarks was released in washington 
the brady plan encourages banks to forgive a substantial portion 
of their loans to heavily indebted countries such as mexico in 
return for guarantees that the rest will be repaid 
those guarantees are to be furnished by the imf and its sister 
international lending agency the world bank 
camdessus said that lengthy negotiations between commerical 
banks and the debtor countries over terms would jeopardize the 
whole strategy given the perilous economic conditions facing many 
of the debtor countries 
camdessus remarks echoed statments made last week by treasury 
undersecretary david c mulford who blamed the slow pace in 
getting the debt reduction effort under way on footdragging by the 
banks 
if the banks fail to cooperate mulford said they could face 
the grim prospect that the debtor nations might decide to stop 
paying on their loans an impasse between the banks and debtor 
nations could trigger a legislated or mandated solution to the 
problem that may be very much more unpleasant for the banks 
mulford warned 
commercial banks have complained that they cant accept major 
reductions in principal and interest payments because they are not 
being offered sufficient financial incentives to do so by the imf 
and the world bank 
but in his paris speech camdessus said that the banks needed to 
give up the illusion that delay in reaching agreement on debt 
reduction proposals being made by the heavily indebted countries 
will force an increase in the amount the imf and other public 
agencies are willing to contribute toward debt reduction 
the imf is not equipped to do more camdessus said adding 
that for the brady approach to succeed it would need equal efforts 
on the part of creditor and debtor countries the commercial banks 
and the international lending organizations such as the imf 
each of the four partners must reconsider its methods and its 
contribution to the common goal he said we shall not succeed 
if any one of these parties chooses to skimp on its contribution or 
hopes to obtain from any of the other three a reduction of its fair 
share of the burden 
major commercial banks are preparing for a meeting in madrid on 
june 7 where they hope to learn more details about what government 
incentives they can expect if they agree to write off a portion of 
the 12 trillion in third world debt 
the sessions will be attended by brady camdessus and e gerald 
corrigan president of the federal reserve bank of new york 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890531-0164 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
what may be one of the best jobs on the east coast 
was uncovered recently when boston edison co sought a rate 
increase budget documents revealed the chairmans chauffeur is 
