into international economic organizations under specified 
conditions 
we should clearly indicate that if the soviet union will play 
by the rules we will welcome it into the game mitchell said 
the majority leader told the senate that the president by his 
proposal this week for mutual cuts in us and soviet forces in 
europe took a major step to address the apparently changed nature 
of soviet communism under president mikhail s gorbachev 
he called for a comprehensive american and nato strategy to 
seize upon change within the soviet union in order to enhance 
western security 
changing circumstances require clear direction and not just a 
reactive or improvised course of action mitchell said 
he said that a symbolic but important first step would be for 
bush to waive the jacksonvanik amendment which was imposed in 1974 
to prohibit us trade concessions until moscow permits free 
immigration of jews and other minority groups 
the legislation was sponsored by the late sen henry m jackson 
dwash and former rep charles vanik dohio 
addressing himself to the president mitchell said i urge him 
to use his authority to waive jacksonvanik for a year thereby 
helping to normalize economic relations and expand the 
possibilities for trade 
he noted that soviet emigration is rising and that the soviet 
government is moving toward legal changes to institutionalize free 
emigration 
now is an appropriate time for the united states to respond to 
change we have sought for more than a decade mitchell said we 
can affirm and encourage further openness within the soviet union 
mitchell said bush should build on that step by stating plainly 
that if the soviet union is able to decentralize its economy and 
institute market mechanisms then the united states would look 
positively upon soviet entry into western economic organizations 
including the world bank and the international monetary fund 
mitchell also said the administration should move quickly in 
negotiations aimed at achieving deep cuts in strategic nuclear arms 
it would be a great loss if we failed to capitalize on the 
opportunity to reduce the far larger strategic arsenals and to 
stabilize the nuclear balance mitchell said 
