<TEXT>
years ago before he was speaker of the house 
james claude wright wrote an affirmation to himself on three 
pieces of scratch paper and vowed to carry it always by now the 
words are surely faded if not soiled 
no person can take from me my inner peace for i shall 
quietly calmly gently pleasantly hold onto it for it is mine 
a gift of god 
i shall be open to new things new thoughts new truths that i 
can learn from other people i have performed well in the past and 
i fully expect success in the future 
i deserve to have happiness career success and economic 
security the lord wants me to have them because i like and 
respect myself i am not adversely affected by the attitudes of 
others if they think they do not like me it is because they do 
not know me 
now jim wright of texas the second most powerful man in 
government most powerful in the democratic party is leaving his 
beloved congress not just adversely affected but laid bare by 
others foes and friends alike whose shared farewell is a sigh of 
relief 
he brought himself down perhaps by failing to abide by that 
pledge to learn new truths namely those arising from profound 
changes in political morality since he came to congress in an era 
of texas bosses and cronies or perhaps his colleagues and the 
nation failed to know him to truly hear him out until it was far 
too late to correct the damage to his credibility and reputation 
that can be argued for years 
eighteen months ago wright merely laughed when rep newt 
gingrich rga began raising cain over reports that the new 
speaker had promoted bulk sales of his book an unscintillating 
compendium of speeches to escape house limits on outside income 
nor did wright seem to perceive any basis for concern over the 
subsequent allegation that he accepted gifts worth 145000 
involving an essentially nowork job for his wife from a texas 
developer friend 
but his world had virtually crashed down upon him by the time he 
rose on the floor of the house late thursday in solemn defense of 
his honor and especially that of wife betty and despite what he 
portrayed as a thorough rebuttal of all the charges he asked in 
tears to give you back this job you gave to me as a 
propitiation for all of this season of bad will 
i dont want to be a party to tearing up this institution 
he said i love it im not a bitter man im a lucky man 
god bless this institution god bless the united states 
he quoted horace greeley fame is a vapor popularity is an 
accident riches take wings those who cheer today may curse 
tomorrow only one thing endures character 
wright as his affirmation suggested did yearn for a secure 
financial life something he didnt have for much of his adulthood 
even as a senior member of the house an abortive senate campaign 
in the 1960s the breakup of his first marriage and the needs of 
four children kept him seriously in debt 
he fell deeply in love with betty hay a longtime staff aide 
after he separated from his first wife mary ethelyn in 1970 but 
to bettys consternation he balked at remarrying because of that 
debt i thought i was doing the lady no favor he said 
she finally prevailed in 1972 i had to talk him into it 
she once recalled i said we can get out of debt we can make 
it and we did 
to this day wright 66 regularly writes romantic poetry to 
her anyone who has seen them together cooing like lovesick 
teenagers knows that his first loyalty is to her 
his salary and investments have put his assets well into six 
figures but wright does not live lavishly he still drives an 
aging chevrolet around washington and lives in the suburban mclean 
va house he bought in 1982 for 228000 a modest figure by 
washington standards 
what the scrappy bushybrowed wright truly burned for since 
arriving in the house 34 years ago was the speakership even if he 
had no illusions about its grandeur he once put it this way i 
had more raw power when i was mayor of weatherford than ive had in 
any job since 
there was the morning he was still in bed when an old woman 
called to complain to the mayor about the wicked little boys 
shooting bb guns at the songbirds in her yard barely had he hung 
up when another woman on the opposite side of town called to 
complain about all the sparrows roosting in her eaves wright drove 
to the first house picked up the boys and transported them to the 
second 
ever since i have yearned for some set of problems amenable 
to that kind of direct action he said you dont find those 
opportunities in the us congress 
perhaps but he never quit trying to find them months before 
his predecessor thomas p tip oneill jr of massachusetts 
stepped down as speaker in late 1986 wright told his colleagues he 
intended nothing less than to tip the balance between the 
legislative and executive branches back in favor of congress 
to some extent that has happened as ronald reagan abandoned 
one domestic initiative after another to congress in his last two 
years at the white house focusing instead on foreign policy and 
even this year embroiled as he was in his own difficulties wright 
and his colleagues have assumed a more equal role with president 
bush in formulating consensus policies over the budget and other 
key issues including latin america 
but republicans complained that within congress itself wright 
was even more partisan than his predecessor with tip there was 
warmth and affection said former rep richard cheney rwy now 
secretary of defense there are no such feelings for jim wright 
sen trent lott of mississippi former house republican whip 
said the house was being run by jim wright and his goons 
even though a 1981 poll by us news amp world report named wright 
as the most respected member of congress he has never lacked for 
detractors even among democrats they included reps dan 
rostenkowski of illinois and john dingell of michigan both of whom 
thought of challenging him for the speakership 
wright surely didnt rise to the leadership heights by the sheer 
force of personality unlike oneill he rarely unwound with his 
colleagues in the cloakrooms or the capitals night spots swapping 
stories and good whiskey 
instead he was a loner who while invariably cordial revealed 
little of himself and family oneill once said you dont have 
anecdotes about jim maybe thats an anecdote 
he is a far greater master of the language than oneill though 
his oratory usually begun with a calculated arch of his trademark 
eyebrows tends toward the tedious and never worked well on 
television 
wright tells the story about how a few years back he was 
growing more and more irritated with the progress of dingells 
energy committee on a complicated bill 
i was forever exhorting them id get impatient and say hey 
look times awastin this is an important problem and the united 
states has got to have a solution to this thing here you are 
sitting around here pecking out and dissecting and extruding to the 
mind the flaccid tissues of longdead issues offensive to god and 
mankind lets get on with it boys 
and finally john dingell said now glorious leader you 
have admonished us in approximately those same terms at least on 
five occasions i would suggest that if youre truly intent upon 
expediting the proceedings we should just designate that speech 
you just made as speech no 1 and whenever you feel impelled to 
exhort us to greater efforts just hold up one finger and well 
know its speech no 1 and it will save us a lot of time 
</TEXT>
