the defense department citing an ongoing 
criminal case against former executives of borden inc has 
temporarily suspended the companys dairy division from doing any 
business with the federal government 
borden was informed of the action in a notice dated may 25 the 
pentagon announced wednesday adding the suspension will remain in 
place pending completion of legal proceedings 
the suspension is based upon adequate evidence to suspect that 
the employees engaged in a conspiracy to suppress and eliminate 
competition by rigging bids for the award and performance of 
contracts to supply milk for school children in florida the 
pentagon said 
larry wilson a spokesman for the defense logistics agency said 
the criminal cases against the former borden executives originated 
in florida and did not involve contracts to provide milk to federal 
agencies 
however because of the nature of the allegations dividing 
up territory for bid rigging et cetera we just thought it was 
prudent to protect the governments interests until we do know if 
similar conduct occurred on our bids wilson said 
the dla spokesman said the defense department during the first 
six months of fiscal 1989 spent 45 million buying borden dairy 
products for military commissaries 
wilson also said the pentagon spent at least 700000 a year in 
the tampa and orlando areas of florida the florida cases involved 
former managers of borden plants in tampa and orlando 
borden executives in new york declined immediate comment 
wednesday on the pentagons announcement or the effect of the 
suspension on the business 
beyond the criminal cases the state of florida has recovered 
32 million from milk producers and distributors involved in what 
has been described as a 10year pricefixing scheme that resulted 
in overcharges for nearly half the states 67 school districts 
of that 32 million total a settlement of 104 million was 
paid by borden inc 
the pentagons suspension was based on the indictments of three 
former borden executives a lamar garrett jack parker tribble 
sr and lenard o jackson 
each of the men were charged in us district court in tampa 
with rigging bids and violating the sherman antitrust act 
under federal procurement regulations the department of defense 
has the authority to act as a socalled executive agent on behalf 
of the entire government when dealing with instances of contracting 
irregularities 
