<TEXT>
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter 
announced wednesday a required 5 percent acreage reduction and 
several other provisions of the 1990 wheat program 
we need more wheat said kelly shipp in explaining why the 
setaside was not higher 
under the law the agriculture secretary each year must decide 
what if any acreage should be set aside in order to keep 
surpluses down yeutter could have asked for a greater acreage 
reduction or none at all 
the 5 percent figure is dramatically lower than past setasides 
during times of great surplus in recent years farmers have been 
asked to cut back the amount of land devoted the crop by as much as 
25 percent 
currently us wheat supplies are low because of the past 
success of the setaside program and because of two years of 
drought 
yeutter said price support loans and purchase rates would be 
195 a bushel a 20 percent reduction from the basic loan and 
purchase rate of 244 
this is the minimum allowed by law and 5 percent below the 1989 
loan and purchase rate of 206 a bushel 
he also set the established target price at 4 a bushel the 
statutory minimum and down about 2 percent from the 1989 target 
price 
furthermore he said would not implement paid land diversions 
marketing loans or related programs no secretary since 1985 has 
implemented these programs for wheat or corn partly because prices 
have been high and there has been no need for them 
