the district of columbia has abandoned plans 
to impose a curfew on teenagers as part of an effort to reduce 
illegal narcotics sales and drugrelated violence in the nations 
capital city officials said wednesday 
last week us district court judge charles r richey struck 
down a proposed city curfew law ruling that the measure violated 
constitutionally protected freedom of association and free speech 
rights 
the judge earlier had struck down a more restrictive curfew 
measure 
charles pearson a spokesman for district councilmember frank 
smith said smith who had helped draft the two previous bills had 
expressed no intention of writing a third 
john c white a spokesman for mayor marion barry said neither 
barry nor other top city officials intended to pursue the matter 
the curfew aimed at keeping teens from congregating in the 
districts notorious openair drug markets would have prohibited 
anyone under 18 from gathering outside after 11 pm sunday through 
thursday and after midnight on friday and saturday the curfew 
would have been lifted each day at 6 am 
the citys second curfew bill included exemptions for teens 
traveling in cars or with their parents or when returning from 
work in addition those returning from school and churchrelated 
functions also were exempt 
however richey ruled that the measure would have subjected 
thousands of lawabiding city teenagers to virtual house 
arrest 
the local chapter of the american civil liberties union brought 
both suits against the city 
