schools they want for their children sister mcnamee said in a 
telephone interview but many now cant because it means paying 
double school taxes and tuition 
many families now do not have a real choice in schools for 
their children because they cant afford that double burden 
the suggested june 9 meeting with bush proposed two weeks ago 
with no direct reply yet was suggested because administrators of 
the big l0 catholic schools systems are meeting in washington 
at that time 
sister leonard also director of educational services in chicago 
besides her post with catholic education administrators said in 
the joint letter to bush 
as catholic educators we have struggled to maintain a viable 
presence in the heart of our urban centers to give the poorest in 
our land a real option a genuine choice for their children of an 
education that is godcentered and which has a moral component to 
it 
parents want this choice but are often unable to exercise it 
for financial reasons 
noting that the 2700 schools in ll major urban dioceses enroll 
a million children at a cost of 14 billion annually she says 
this saves the country 2 billion annually since perpupil costs in 
public schools range from 4l00 to 6900 per year 
citing remarks by bush that the govenment cannot afford to help 
parents of children in nonpublic schools she said 
we strongly disagree we believe faced with the present 
national crisis in education that you cannot afford not to help 
