<TEXT>
international business machines corp has 
elected a new president but the technologyminded executive is not 
in line to be chairman of the worlds largest computer company 
because he is older than the current officeholder 
jack d kuehler the new president is 56 john f akers the 
chairman and chief executive is 54 
the new job for kuehler is a recognition of his contributions in 
a 31year career at the company ibm spokesman peter judice said 
tuesday in announcing kuehlers promotion 
kuehlers duties at ibms armonk ny headquarters will be 
about the same as they were in his former job of vice chairman 
although he will have slightly more authority judice said the 
vice chairmanship will be left vacant for now 
ibm has no mandatory retirement age but top executives make a 
practice of relinquishing their jobs at age 60 that gives akers 
potentially six more years as chairman 
kuehlers predecessor as president was akers himself akers 
became president in february 1983 added the title of chief 
executive in february 1985 and added the chairmanship in june 1986 
at the unusually young age of 51 
as vice chairman kuehlers job under the bylaws was to assist 
the chairman as president the bylaws state that he is to run the 
business after the chairman and can act for the chairman 
its a somewhat more substantive position judice said 
kuehler is known within ibm as a technology expert in contrast 
to akers whose main strength is in marketing 
kuehler began with the company as an associate engineer at the 
san jose research laboratory in 1958 he was elected to the board 
of directors in 1986 and executive vice president in march 1987 
he was named ibm vice chairman of the board in january 1988 and 
given responsibility for overseeing ibm united states the 
organization headed by terry lautenbach that is responsible for all 
ibm activities in the united states as well as worldwide 
development he also has overseen corporate staffs in charge of 
manufacturing and systems and programming 
kuehler will keep those responsibilities as president 
