<TEXT>
orders to us factories for manufactured 
goods rose 27 percent in april the best showing in four months 
the government reported today 
the commerce department said orders for durable and nondurable 
goods climbed to a seasonally adjusted 2394 billion last month 
after rising 07 percent in march and dropping during the first two 
months of the year 
aprils increase reflected higher demand in a variety of 
industry categories and would have been even stronger were it not 
for a 158 percent drop in defense orders which are subject to 
wide swings depending on when big contracts are signed 
excluding defense all other orders were up 36 percent in april 
after falling 03 percent in march and 27 percent in february 
aprils upturn in factory orders was in line with other recent 
reports on the economys performance which analysts say suggest 
that while growth is slowing a recession is not imminent 
it was the strongest gain since a 47 percent increase in orders 
last december 
earlier today the commerce department reported that its chief 
economic forecasting gauge the index of leading economic 
indicators shot up 08 percent in april after declining during the 
previous two months 
todays report on factory orders showed that in the volatile 
transportation category orders rose 14 percent in april after 
jmping 11 percent in march and falling 76 percent in february 
excluding transportation all other orders were up 30 percent 
last month after falling during the previous two months 
orders for nondefense capital goods meanwhile posted a strong 
61 percent gain in april after rising 25 percent in march the 
category is considered a good barometer of business investment 
plans 
the overall increase in factory orders last month included a 30 
percent jump in demand for big ticket durable goods and a 24 
percent rise in orders for nondurables 
orders for durable goods items expected to last at least three 
years rose to a seasonally adjusted 1292 billion in april after 
rising 10 percent in march 
the april increase in orders for durable goods included gains in 
most industries led by a 93 percent rise in demand for electrical 
machinery and a 60 percent jump in orders for primary metals such 
as steel 
orders for nondurable goods meanwhile rose to a seasonally 
adjusted 1102 billion after rising 04 percent in march nearly 
half of the april increase was in the petroleum refining industry 
shipments of manufactured goods rose 24 percent in april to a 
seasonally adjusted 2334 billion following three consecutive 
declines 
