the equitable of iowa cos is looking 
for a buyer for its younkers department store chain saying 
wednesday it would use the proceeds to expand its insurance 
business 
equitable said it would begin soliciting bids in the next three 
weeks and has retained the new york investment firm of salomon 
brothers inc to advise the company on offers for the chain that 
has stores in iowa nebraska illinois minnesota and south dakota 
and had sales last year of 313 million 
a sale is not expected to occur until early fall 
i think its a wise move said analyst vita marino at 
firemark insurance research a consulting and investment banking 
firm at parsippany nj many companies in the industry who 
diversified in the last decade are now streamlining their 
operations 
investors appeared to cheer the news in overthecounter 
trading equitable of iowa stock rose 150 a share to 2975 in 
wednesdays session 
analyst jeff hopson at the st louis investment firm ag 
edwards amp sons inc estimated a minimum value of 20 a share for 
younkers or 140 million 
the company has refused to speculate on what a sale would bring 
or who would buy its retail business but has valued younkers at a 
minimum of 73 million 
hopson said a logical suitor might be dillard department stores 
inc of little rock ark but that he expected several other 
companies also would be interested a call seeking comment from 
dillards was not returned 
asked about the possibility of a management buyout tom gould 
the president of younkers said managers have decided to keep their 
options open 
its better to wait and see what the opportunities are he 
said 
gould said younkers has outperformed the industry in recent 
years but it would take tremendous amounts of capital to continue 
the performance 
younkers earned 83 million on 313 million in sales last year 
and has been improving steadily in recent years in 1984 for 
example it earned 680000 on sales of 1886 million 
equitable of iowa which purchased younkers in 1979 had 
earnings of 367 million on 5097 million in revenue last year 
just two years ago it acquired the elevenstore brandeis chain for 
younkers at a cost of 60 million 
in its announcement in des moines where it is based equitable 
said the decision to seek a buyer for younkers reflects an attempt 
to redirect its capital from its retail interests to its insurance 
business 
at present we see significant growth potential in both 
businesses but unfortunately this growth would require more 
capital than is currently available said fred hubbell the chief 
executive of equitable of iowa 
the company said it would difficult and risky to attempt to 
provide enough money to expand both businesses at the same time 
our core life insurance business and in particular our 
annuities business offers great future promise hubbell said 
we have greater management experience and expertise in insurance 
as a result we believe it is appropriate at this time to seek a 
buyer for younkers 
