<TEXT>
singer co chairman paul a bilzerian resumed 
testifying at his federal securities fraud trial wednesday but 
only after his lawyers revamped their case to compensate for an 
unfavorable ruling by the judge 
on tuesday us district robert j ward ruled that if bilzerian 
testified that he didnt believe he was breaking the law in two 
takeover attempts it would open up a line of questioning to 
prosecutors about what his lawyers told him at the time 
such lawyerclient conversations are usually confidential under 
the socalled attorneyclient privilege 
when ward ruled that privilege would be waived if bilzerian was 
asked and answered certain questions by his defense lawyers they 
asked for an adjornment to reconsider their strategy 
we have determined an your honor defense attorney arthur 
mathews told ward at the beginning of wednesdays session that we 
do not intend to pursue anything upon the direct examination of mr 
bilzerian that would waive the attorneyclient privilege 
mathews added later we have restructured our planned 
examination of mr bilzerian 
under mathews questioning bilzerian described his acquisition 
of stock in hh robertson co manufacturing and construction 
concern and apparelmaker cluett peabody amp co two transactions 
listed in the indictmet against him 
his testimony was to continue thursday 
bilzerian 38 of tampa fla is accused of conspiracy 
violating securities and tax laws and making false statements in 
connection with four failed takeover attempts in 1985 and 1986 
none of the charges involve bilzerians 106 billion takeover 
of singer last year 
in two of those four transactions the 1985 purchase of cluett 
peabody amp co shares and the 1986 purchase of hammermill paper co 
stock the government contends bilzerian falsely claimed to be 
using millions of dollars of his own money when most of the money 
actually was raised by others 
but the defense has contended bilzerian acted in good faith 
and did not believe he was breaking the law in filing misleading 
documents with the securities and exchange commission 
in statements he made to the sec in 1988 bilzerian said he was 
merely following his thenlawyers advice when he supplied 
misleading information on sec forms 
ward however said by taking the witness stand and invoking 
that good faith defense under questioning by his own lawyers 
bilzerian was waiving the attorneyclient privilege and prosecutors 
could ask on cross examination what was the basis for his belief 
that he was not breaking any laws more specifically what had 
his lawyers told him at the time 
bilzerian was not required to testify 
if convicted bilzerian faces a maximum penalty of five years in 
jail and a 250000 fine on each count 
