<TEXT>
the federal communications is recommending to 
congress that it abolish a 13yearold copyright system that allows 
cable television operators to pay a percentage of their income to 
retransmit overtheair tv programs officials said wednesday 
the commission in a ruling it made tuesday and released 
wednesday said cable tv companies should negotiate with 
broadcasters and producers on a casebycase basis for programs 
critics of that approach say it would be very costly for cable 
operators to negotiate for every program individually and could 
result in fewer programs being made available to cable subscribers 
or cause subscription costs to go up 
congress in 1976 compelled broadcasters and program owners to 
allow cable operators to retransmit their programs in return for 
this compulsory license cable companies were required to pay a 
specified percentage of their revenues to the us copyright 
office the offices copyright royalty tribunal decides how to 
allocate the fees among broadcasters program owners and entities 
such as sports franchises 
in establishing the rules congress reasoned that the costs of 
working out contracts for every program would stymy the infant 
cable tv industry 
the cable industry last year paid 188 million in compulsory 
license fees according to lynn mcreynolds a spokeswoman for the 
national cable television association 
fcc chairman dennis patrick said the current system impedes 
the efficient functioning of the market and weakens the 
incentives of producers to respond to consumers tastes and 
programming preferences 
he said it also subsidizes program acquisition by cable 
operators and disadvantages competitive alternatives to cable 
but james mooney president of the cable association said the 
fcc seems to be a little off the deep end 
mooney noted that congress last year extended the present 
copyright system to companies that package tv programs for delivery 
to backyard satellite dish owners rather than making those 
packagers negotiate for shows one at a time 
congress and the commission seem not to share the same view on 
these matters mooney said in a statement 
the commission last year made a preliminary decision to 
recommend repeal of the compulsory license rules for programs that 
come from stations located outside local viewing areas 
superstations such as wtbs in atlanta and wgn in chicago are 
examples of these socalled distant signals 
cable operators use satellites or microwave systems to relay 
these signals around the nation and then pipe them into homes 
locally 
in its new decision the fcc recommended that the rules be 
repealed for all signals both from distant broadcasters and from 
local broadcasters such as channels 4 7 9 and so on 
commissioner patricia dennis concurred with patrick in the 
ruling commissioner james quello concurred with repealing the 
distant signal provision but he argued for keeping the compulsory 
license for local signals 
it is conceivable that under full copyright liability cable 
operators may choose not to carry local broadcast signals due to 
the costs of obtaining rights to retransmit the programs quello 
said 
he said the fcc should instead recommend that congress 
reimpose rules requiring cable systems to carry all local broadcast 
stations he said these mustcarry rules shouldnt exist 
without compulsory license for local signals 
he also disputed the agency staffs contention that costs of 
negotiating contracts were lower today per subscriber than in 
1976 
mooney said it was surprising the commission was 
recommending repeal of the rules for local signals 
he said that would create a situation in which cable could not 
even retransmit local signals by joint agreement the original 
rights owners in hollywood would have to consent too presumably 
for a price 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

